He believed in the natural rights of people, like freedom and stuff, and he thought they were all connected - if one was taken away, they'd all suffer. He wanted those rights to be totally off-limits to the government. He thought the "state of nature" was all about the strong and mean taking advantage, but in civilization, that shouldn't be how it goes down.

To make this perfect society, Taylor thought a government should be built with both good and bad in mind. He was super strict about his ideas on good and evil, and he said that a government's virtues and flaws are basically human too. He thought good principles should be about protecting people's property, improving farming, and not being too capitalist, and that a government with good principles would work out okay no matter who's in charge, even if they're all about personal gain. But, he believed that self-interest is basically human nature, and it's only bad when it's all about taking from others. A good government is needed to keep people's bad sides in check, but it's gotta be watched closely so it doesn't get worse.

Taylor was like a lot of other Republicans back then - he wanted the Constitution to be taken super literally, with the government only having the powers it was given. He thought a big government is expensive and might be a dictatorship, but he also didn't want it to be too simple or literal, 'cause that could lead to problems. He even thought the Declaration of Independence was the real deal, 'cause it said the US was a bunch of states, not just one country.

Looking back at the data in Figure 17, it's clear that there was a huge drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. It was pretty discouraging and it's hard to figure out why this happened. One possible reason could be the onset of winter at our New England campus, which usually leads to fewer people commuting by bike or on foot. Also, with the end of the fall semester, people are super busy with schoolwork, grades, and other stuff, so it's easy to forget about the commuter log. Plus, December is the start of the holiday season and everyone's on break, which means fewer people need to come to campus. It wasn't until the spring semester picked up again in late January that things started to look up. However, the low number of submissions in February still didn't make sense. I wondered if it's just that any project like this has a burst of energy at the beginning that eventually fades away. To combat this, we tried the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which actually worked and got people excited again. It was tough to keep the project going, especially with the holiday and semester breaks that always come up in college. 

Another challenge for this project (and probably any other commuting project) is that people really love the freedom, independence, and flexibility that comes with driving their own cars. This is just how our culture is. To get people to switch to alternative modes of commuting, we need to offer some pretty sweet incentives. So, we gave out gift cards to all sorts of places like restaurants, coffee shops, and even a local bookstore. It would've been interesting to see how bigger prizes, like a new bike or a hybrid car, would've affected participation. Maybe it could've even helped us get back on track after that dip in engagement. One thing that didn't change throughout the project was the kind of prizes we offered. If we had announced some bigger prizes in the middle of the project, like a bike in December and a hybrid car in January, it might've made people more excited to participate. The gift cards were cool at first, but who wouldn't be even more stoked if they knew they could win a sick new set of wheels?

I recently learned about exchange traded funds, or ETFs for short. These securities are super flexible and offer the benefits of owning individual stocks, like being able to sell short or buy on margin, but they also give you the diversification of an index fund. Plus, the expense ratios of ETFs are way lower than those of the average mutual fund. However, there are some downsides to consider, like the commission fees you pay on each trade, just like when you're buying or selling a stock. Another cool thing about ETFs is the huge variety of funds available, but it's always a good idea for smart investors to check if the benefits they're promised really live up to their hype. For this project, we're going to take a closer look at the ETF IHF and see how its top 10 holdings stack up against owning a diversified portfolio of the same stocks. We're only looking at the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets, since going over every single holding would be a bit too much. Here's what we found:

To get a better sense of how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF IHF, we can calculate the contributions of each stock to its Beta and Return, assuming a portfolio made up entirely of these 10 stocks in the same proportions as the ETF holds them. Check out the chart below to see the results.

From the chart, it's clear that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could give you a return that's 6.11% higher than the ETF IHF, which is a pretty sweet 16% boost. What's more, the Beta of this portfolio is 0.12 lower than the ETF's, which could be a good thing. But before we get too excited, we need to make sure these results aren't just a fluke. To do that, we've calculated the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalized it to 100% to compare it to the ETF IHF's standard deviation. Stay tuned to see what we find out!

"Dream-Land" is widely considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's best poems. In this poem, Poe uses the term "Thulé" which, according to Mabbott, has its roots in Virgil's work. Virgil used "Thulé" to describe an island north of Britain, the edge of the known world in Greek mythology. But what's more interesting is that Poe was heavily influenced by German authors, and one in particular - Gothe. Poe's familiarity with Gothe's writing is evident in his use of "Thulé". 

This connection is reinforced by Karl J. Arndt's observation in his book on Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon, which notes the striking similarities between the two poems, suggesting that Poe was drawing inspiration from Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature also highlights Gothe's notable works, including the poetic drama Faust, which was published in two parts, first in 1808 and then in 1832, the year of Gothe's passing. Within Faust, there's a poem called "The King of Thulé" that tells the story of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. The king then becomes a heavy drinker, mourning his lost love. He eventually decides it's his time to die and passes on his possessions, save for the goblet, and throws it into the ocean before taking his own life. The similarities between the King of Thulé and the character in "Dream-Land" are uncanny, and some might see it as a darker reflection of Poe's own struggles with loss and addiction. Interestingly, Faust was later adapted into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe referenced "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum". 

Poe references "ultrama Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum", but in "Dream-Land", he uses "Thule" as a bookend, framing the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces, with "Dream-Land" echoing the themes of loss, loneliness, and a desolate landscape found in "The King of Thulé". The speaker in "Dream-Land" describes Thule as a dark, lonely place haunted by the ghosts of dead friends, a world devoid of color. This mirrors the King of Thulé's experience after losing his wife, and it's as if Poe is stepping into Goethe's poem. Given Poe's respect for Tennyson, it's likely he would have been familiar with Goethe's work, and the many reproductions of his works that were being published at the time further solidified Poe's connection to Goethe's writing.

So, I'm wondering if a person could get punitive damages in court if they got hurt in a grocery store after slipping on an applesauce spill because the manager was super careless. He knew there was a mess, but he didn't bother to clean it up for over half an hour because he was eating dinner. He'd been told about the spill not once, but twice. A judge wouldn't just dismiss the person's claim for punitive damages. To get those damages, the person would have to show that the manager did something super bad on purpose, like ignoring the harm it could cause. They'd also have to prove that the manager's actions were really bad and showed a huge disregard for how his actions could affect others. In this case, the person could argue that the manager should have known that not cleaning up the spill would hurt someone, especially since multiple people slipped on the same thing in the months leading up to the accident. The manager still didn't take action, even after knowing this. The person's argument that the manager's actions were really bad is kinda weak, but it's still a valid point since there were six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009 and the manager still didn't do anything to keep his store safe.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee told the manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in the store. Martin said he was eating dinner and didn't have time to deal with customer complaints. Fifteen minutes later, another employee told him again, but he still didn't do anything. At 5:30 pm, the person who got hurt, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and got seriously hurt. Before that, there were five other slip-and-fall incidents in the same store in 2009. Now Palmer is suing the store for both compensation and punitive damages, and we're looking at whether to file a motion to get the punitive damage claim thrown out.

In California, a person can get punitive damages if the other person did something super mean, like being really cruel or lying to them. The law says that's when someone acts on purpose to hurt someone, or when they don't intend to hurt someone, but they do something really bad and show a huge disregard for other people's safety. The court has said that's when someone knows their actions could cause harm and they still do it anyway.

It's crazy how a class I took almost four years ago in Islam at CBC still has me thinking about this topic.  The question of whether Islam is a hostile religion was a huge deal back then, and I think it's more relevant now than ever.  Since 9/11, I've noticed that mass media has gone from being really negative about Islam and extremists to being super tolerant of it in America - it's like a total 180.  In 2001, I don't think a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with his obvious Muslim background, would've even been a possibility.

I'm actually pretty fascinated by the biography of the Prophet Muhammad.  What I learned about him seems to contradict the personality people usually think of when they hear his name.  I thought he was some kind of conqueror who forced people to convert to Islam, but the biography paints a totally different picture - Muhammad as a humble martyr who was misunderstood and even humbled himself to others.  It's like people came to see the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out one by one. 

It's wild how similar some of his 'miracles' are to those of Jesus - like when he multiplied mutton and milk to feed a huge crowd.  The way it's written makes me think the authors wanted Muhammad to be seen as a prophet who didn't need to prove anything, but just lived in truth and did miracles.  To me, this is a major problem because it downplays the life and miracles of Jesus.  It's like they're trying to take credit for Jesus' life by portraying Muhammad as a similar figure.

There are also a lot of stories in the biography that seem like they're trying to show how people came to Islam on their own, but most of them are third-hand accounts.  I'm not a fan of this because it makes the stories seem suspicious and takes away from their impact.  I think their idea was that it provided proof of the truth of the stories, but it actually does the opposite.

What really gets me is how the biography tries to make Muhammad out to be this awesome, godly man who was humble, wise, and gentle.  But history says otherwise - Muhammad was a pretty powerful guy who rose to power in a way that doesn't exactly scream 'gentle'.  I wonder if Muslims today know the real story behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings and values that Jesus had during his lifetime were pretty much left behind in the development of Christianity after he passed away.  If we look at the history of Christianity, it's like watching a ship drift further and further away from its original course. It's clear that today, more and more people are starting to wake up and realize that they've been sailing in the wrong direction. While some traditional folks will stick to what they've been taught, they might not be enough to steer the whole crew back on track. A growing number of people will become more aware of their history and start to crave a return to the original intentions of Jesus and his teachings. It might take a while – decades or even centuries – but it's inevitable that eventually, there will be a major shift. The tide of Christian history will start moving in reverse, stripping away the extra baggage that's accumulated over time, and getting back to the basics. It'll be like rewinding a tape, until all that's left is a clear picture of what Jesus actually preached about. 

This movement will sweep across countries like the US and Europe, influencing millions and bringing people back to the essentials of Jesus' teachings. The church, as an institution, will still be strong enough to lead the way. But as a result of this shift, the diverse and complex landscape of Christianity will simplify into more uniformity. Instead of seeing a million different interpretations and practices, we'll see more and more similarities across the board. Human history's full of these kinds of reversals – think of how Christians used to be persecuted by the Roman Empire, but later it became a Christian institution. We've seen how our country moved from slavery to equality for African-Americans. This big reversal that's coming in the future will happen within Christianity, and it'll be a journey back to the source, leaving diversity behind. A key part of this process will be learning to interpret Jesus' words in a metaphorical way, rather than taking them literally. So, what happened to Jesus' teachings over time?

Looking way back into history, we find that the only thing before Christianity was Judaism. The core of this faith included monotheism, the idea of a divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures. By the time the Romans took over Jerusalem in 63 BCE, the Jewish people weren't a single, unified group. They were divided into different factions, like the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the common folk.

I think that The Jungle really shows us what people are like deep down inside - we're all pretty greedy and self-centered. We only want to make our own lives as good as possible and look out for ourselves, but we don't really care about anyone else. The Jungle shows this in a lot of ways, but one of the most obvious is with the bosses of the big factories. All they care about is making their companies super successful and getting as much money as possible. They don't care if anyone gets hurt or if anything gets in their way. Upton Sinclair's writing, like when he says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky", really paints a picture of all the damage that's being done. He's showing how the bosses don't care about anyone or anything that might get hurt by their factories - the pollution, the animal waste, none of it matters to them.

The bosses also didn't care about their employees, who were working super hard to make them rich. They'd do whatever it took to make a little extra money, and they didn't care who got hurt in the process, "So it was like one big pot of jealousy and hatred; nobody had any loyalty or decency, and nobody was worth anything more than a dollar". They made their employees work super long hours and then fired them randomly without any help or notice. Back when The Jungle was written, there weren't really any laws to protect workers, so the bosses could do whatever they wanted. The people who worked and lived in Packingtown were basically expected to just deal with the terrible conditions - nobody was there to help them. There were some unions, but they mostly just made money off the workers. The workers were treated like slaves, and that's basically what they were - they were stuck in a system with no way out, and they were described as being as miserable as people were under slavery.

Authors often use various techniques to shape the mood or attitude of their readers towards significant topics. Some techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald masterfully employs several of these techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. He sometimes pairs words that normally don't go together to create a distinct atmosphere around an object or subject. At other times, he assigns meaning to a symbol, and then uses it to evoke a certain feeling. Fitzgerald frequently uses this second technique with colors, particularly gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald develops the meanings of white/gray and then uses them to create a particular impression of a significant object.

Fitzgerald builds up the meaning of white/gray by repeatedly using them in the novel. He associates white with being fancy and high-class, with gray being more dull and faded. Fitzgerald introduces this association early on, showing how characters like Daisy and Jordan are always "in white" (8). Everyone at parties is wearing white, from Nick's "white flannels" (41) to Tom's "white shirt" (36). Even the environment is described as having a uniform appearance: the "halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40) when Nick isn't at a party. To reinforce this association, Fitzgerald describes ordinary, insignificant things with these colors: Nick goes "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56), and people's names are now "gray names" (61) on Nick's schedule. He even uses these colors to describe plain or common people and places: Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood" (19) together, there are "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, and the "Italian child" in the railroad is "gray" (26).

After establishing the meaning of white/gray, Fitzgerald uses them to convey unimportance or uniformity around certain subjects. He starts by applying this technique to Daisy. After a long time without any significant use of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster" (74), making her seem less like a character and more like an accessory Gatsby wants and longs for. Fitzgerald uses this technique more extensively around Daisy to give her an impression of being a uniform addition, for instance, there's a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18), and she's again in a "white" (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is a goldmine for agricultural production thanks to its awesome weather. They grow a lot of stuff there like tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squashes, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. It's super in-demand to buy organic food directly from local farmers in the area, with so many people waiting in line to get their hands on it. People are also super into getting their eggs and milk from organic farms. Some of these farms even let people come and explore their operations, and you can go hiking, birdwatching, or just chill there. It's like a win-win situation for the landowner, 'cause they get to get some cash and also help out the environment. This is especially cool 'cause it lets them qualify for government programs that'll help 'em out.

Not only does organic farming bring in some cash, it also makes the area way more diverse in terms of plants and animals. Without all the chemicals, the soil and water are basically a party for all the little critters. However, it's not all sunshine and rainbows - organic farming can be more expensive in some ways. For example, it takes a lot more work to get rid of pests and weeds, and you gotta put in extra effort to fertilize the soil without using chemicals. Plus, you might end up losing more stuff than you would with regular farming methods. And, if you're a small farm, you're at a disadvantage 'cause big farms are way more efficient. There are other things you can do to help the environment that aren't even about organic farming, like planting special crops to keep pests away, rotating your animals to keep the land healthy, and getting rid of invasive species. All these things can be a real time suck, though.

For this example, I chose a piece of land in the East County Southern Foothills of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. It's a 160-acre chunk of chaparral, grassland, and oak woodland right next to the Cleveland National Forest. They're still working on the plan, but it's got over a hundred different plants and animals on the list, some of which are super endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, and the California gnatcatcher. Others are in danger of becoming endangered, like the burrowing owl. This land has been home to Native Americans for who-knows-how-long and was later settled by cattle ranchers and people who sold cordwood back in the 1800s. It was part of an original homestead, so it was probably used for grazing and making wood for a long time.

I picked a real estate listing and looked up what government programs are out there to help small farmers save cash and keep their operations eco-friendly. To get an idea of what it's like, I looked at an actual organic farm in the same area.

Culture plays a big role in any negotiation. You can figure out a lot about a culture by looking at what it's not, rather than what it actually is. This culture thing isn't one big, uniform thing - it's super diverse and can change depending on the situation. Statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are way too broad and oversimplify things. It's way more helpful to understand what a culture means in this specific situation and how that culture might affect the conversation. When you're dealing with a foreign culture, you're gonna relate to it in your own way, and comparisons are gonna pop up.

It can take some work to grasp another culture or mindset - you might have to study its history, or try to understand its prejudices. Instead of judging or trying to change a culture, just accept it for what it is and work with it. This is especially true in negotiations, especially if you're in a weaker position. If you're "on the road" and need to navigate a different culture, showing respect for their traditions and values can actually help you get past any cultural barriers and move the conversation forward.

It's also worth noting that culture isn't just about where you come from or where you're going - it can be something as small as a company's corporate culture. For example, some companies are super strict about working hours, while others are way more relaxed. You can see this in employee dress codes, the way people communicate, and even how they hire people. Take American corporate culture - it's totally different from company to company (and even within companies, it can vary from region to region). Some cultures seem super uniform, but that just means you gotta dig deeper.

Understanding values is even more important because it helps you understand why a culture does things a certain way. If saving face or keeping things harmonious is a big deal in a culture, you won't see anyone publicly embarrassing themselves or their boss to get ahead. On the other hand, if a culture values getting a tough deal, they won't be in a rush to settle. Knowing these kinds of things can really help before you get to the negotiation table. But you should also try to learn a bit about your opponent as an individual to make the negotiations go smoothly.

There's this famous Bible verse - "The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God.'" - and it's found in Psalm 14. St. Anselm used this quote to start his argument for the existence of God. It's also believed by another big thinker, Thomas Aquinas. Since both of them are trying to prove the same idea, we'll just assume they're both right, because if we use a different idea of God, it'd be hard to compare their arguments. If we do that, it's like comparing apples and oranges. Let's just say they both believe in the Christian God for simplicity's sake. Now, I think both of them have some good points, but neither of them really gives a complete reason to believe in God.

Let's start with St. Anselm. He says that we can understand God by looking inside ourselves. He thinks that because we can't really imagine a world without God, that means God must be real. This idea is really like looking at what we already know inside our minds and using that to figure out the truth about God. St. Anselm says we don't need any other proof, that our own understanding is enough. This way of thinking is often called faith in Christian texts. It's like trusting something even if we can't prove it.

This is different from how Thomas Aquinas thinks. He says that we can prove God exists using logic and things we can see, not just faith. This would be super helpful for spreading the word about Christianity because people wouldn't have to believe it just because someone told them to. They could use their brains to figure it out. St. Thomas presents five different logical reasons to believe in God: change, cause and effect, why things exist, how good things are ranked, and how things fit together. He shows that God is the only thing that makes sense. If someone tells you you're missing a puzzle piece, you can figure out what it's like without actually seeing it.

So, I'm going to tell you about this ancient dude named Buddha, who lived a gazillion years ago, somewhere around the 5th or 6th century BCE. He was a prince, but not just any prince – he was going to become the Buddha. Over time, he ditched the whole royal thing and got enlightened. His teachings ended up creating Buddhism, the most 'orthodox' sect of which is called Theravada Buddhism. This whole thing is over 2,500 years old now, and it's changed a lot since Buddha's time. You can see this by looking at Sri Lanka, which is a Theravada nation, and their annual water-cutting ceremony. It's a big deal, with monks and regular folks participating, but Buddha never actually talked about anything like that. These changes go all the way from the surface-level stuff to the core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community has had to adapt its rules and principles over time, whether it's due to external or internal factors, or even both. External factors are basically anything that comes from non-Buddhists, while internal factors are stuff that happens within the Buddhist community itself.

There are some terms that'll come up a lot in this discussion. Internal factors are basically things that come from within the Buddhist community, no matter if someone's a monk or not. External factors are anything that comes from outside the community. A hostile factor is anything that damages or tries to damage the community – basically, anything that has a negative view of Buddhism. A benign factor is something that doesn't want to hurt or help the community, but might end up doing one or the other by accident.

First off, we need to get a handle on the basics of Theravada Buddhism – the core principles that make it tick. Buddhists find refuge in the three jewels: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially the Pali Canon, which includes the Tripitaka – the three baskets of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka is all about the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka is about the rules for monks and layfolk, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka is all about the metaphysical stuff, like no soul, inherent suffering, and the impermanence of everything. Understanding these ideas is key to ending Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. Along with that, you'll also be done with lobha – desire, dosa – hatred, and moha – delusion when you get enlightened. The Vinaya Pitaka lays out the rules for living for both monks and layfolk. For regular folks, there are five precepts (don't kill, don't lie, don't steal, don't get all crazy with sex, and don't get drunk). Monks have a lot more rules to follow. The fundamental idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths: life is suffering (Dukkha), attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome, and so on.

You won't believe the epic rivalry that went down between the US and Mexico for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893.  It was like, a major thing (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145).  The rivalry was like, at its peak during the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848, where the US totally came at Mexico, kicked its butt, and took Texas and the Southwest as its own (I'm talking the US, not me, I wasn't born yet).  We're not the only ones, though - lots of countries with a history of clashes with their neighbors.  It's pretty common for countries that share borders to have major disagreements that fuel their rivalry (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31).  The US and Mexico were no exception - our rivalry started with some major disagreements over stuff like religion, culture, and tradition.  It's like, a big clash of interests (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31).  

This whole rivalry thing isn't unique to us, though.  Other countries that share borders often develop similar rivalries.  David M. Pletcher (1977) said, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41).  Both of these countries are, like, right next to the US, and we've had a rivalry with them for a while.  Other countries in Latin America, though, have generally gotten along with us just fine.  

Religion was a major point of contention between the US and Mexico, just like it has been in many other countries throughout history.  Sally Frahm (2001) said that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86).  It's kinda like how the Cold War was both an ideological struggle and a competition over interests, but with us, it was more about our differing views on religion.  We got these feelings of distrust from our colonial past with the English and Spanish, and that just made things worse (Diehl and Goerts 2000).  

Diehl and Goerts (2000) listed 17 major disputes between the US and Mexico during that 57-year rivalry period.  Most of those disputes were about territorial issues, like border raids from Mexico into the US and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from American border towns were a huge problem until we and Mexico both started cracking down on our borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).  Schmitt (1974) said that the rivalry started to die down as Mexico became more dependent on the US and our goals changed from expansion to economic intervention in Mexico (p. 109-110).

I was hit with an unexpected illness fifteen years ago that left me in a state of disability that I had never anticipated. I was working as a nurse at the time and had chosen the profession to escape the uncertainty of my childhood. People kept telling me, "You'll always be able to find work; people will always need help." But my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist - maybe a little bit of both. Despite the doubts, I stuck with nursing.

Now, I'm 46 and single, living on Social Security Disability after fifteen years. I've got nothing to show for it, and every day feels like a struggle to stay afloat. I'm still in a constant state of uncertainty, but one thing is clear - without the support of my family and a few close friends, I wouldn't have made it this far. When disaster strikes, you realize how weak you are, not strong.

My point is that life is full of emergencies, big and small, and no matter how prepared you are, some things are just too big to handle on your own. We need to stop putting all our faith in the government and learn to rely on each other instead. Trusting others and asking for help is a much better approach than building individual fallout shelters.

The idea of "rugged individualism" that the Conservatives in the US love to talk about isn't what kept our ancestors going in hard times. It was actually compassion, mutual respect, and sharing resources that got them through. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it alone - they worked together.

So, yes, be prepared and have your disaster kit ready. I've got mine set up with first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, and lots of other essentials. But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors and build a community that can support each other. It's a much better approach than going it alone.

I've been wondering why organisms evolve the way they do and whether there are any limits that shape the direction of evolutionary change. Even back in 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said that it's almost impossible for biologists to put the fundamentals of organic forms into mathematical terms, and we're still not there yet. But lately, scientists have started using math to study the development of shell growth in mollusks, looking at both how they grow over their lifetime and how their ancestors evolved (think Raup and Stanley from 1981). Our research is trying to figure out how using math to model this growth, combined with actual experiments, can help us understand why and how certain traits develop during evolution. To do this, we took X-ray images of different species of Prunum and used them to identify factors that we could use to model different shell shapes. We plugged these factors into a special computer program called CerioShell (created by Stone in 1995) to see what different shapes might be possible. Then we combined these results with experiments and observations to better understand how big evolutionary changes happen in this group of animals.

A shell can be thought of as a tube that spins around in space, kind of like a 360-degree turn. These turns are called whorls, and they're like layers that spiral around an imaginary middle point, which is called the columella. The speed at which these layers grow can be different, and the lines that separate them are called sutures. In most shells, the biggest layer is the last one (the body whorl), and the spire is all the layers except that one. The pointy end is called the apex, and the other end is called the base. The animal sticks out of its shell through a hole called the aperture.

Shells can be looked at in different ways, like from the top or bottom, or from the side. Most people look at shells with the hole facing them and the pointy end up.

Now, let's talk about how to count the layers of a shell. First, you look at the top of the shell, and then you find the line where the first layer starts. Then you draw a line down the middle of the shell, and count the layers from there. You can even estimate layers that are almost complete.

A shell can be thought of as a series of holes that move through time and space as the animal builds its shell. You can actually track the path of the hole by looking at the center of each layer and how big the hole is. This path can be shown as a graph or math problem. Once you have a math problem, you can change the variables and see how it affects the way the shell grows.

The rate of newborn and infant deaths in Indonesia has pretty much stayed the same for the last ten years.  Even though they're making progress in some areas, like water and sanitation, they're missing the mark on reducing child and mom health problems.  I'm going to break down the reasons why, and it shows that Indonesia needs to focus on making their health system stronger instead of just having a bunch of programs.

They've made some improvements in getting health workers to be present at births, with 72% of births meeting this goal.  But let's not get too excited – it's not all good news.  This number includes traditional workers, like midwives, who can't help if things get complicated.  It's kind of like a puzzle, and some of the pieces are still missing.  Also, there's been a drop in the number of kids under five getting medical help for diarrhea.  And don't even get me started on post-natal care – it's a total concern, and the data isn't even complete.

C-section rates are still way too low, around 4%.  And this number has its own problems too.  In cities, c-sections make up 7% of births, but in the countryside, it's only 2%.  This shows us that there's a big gap in healthcare access between cities and the country.  It's like having a health system with a big gap in the middle.

Another problem is that the rich have way more access to healthcare than the poor.  There's a 27% difference between the richest and poorest families.  It's pretty obvious that the poor are getting left behind because healthcare costs are just too high.  So, what's next?  How do we fix this?  The question is, should Indonesia focus on making one specific area better or strengthen their whole health system?  It seems like the latter would be the way to go, but there are some things to consider.

Here's the thing: focusing on one area can be pretty tempting.  It's easy to see results, and it's a more manageable goal.  But there are some downsides.  If you put too much money into one area, the other areas are going to suffer.  And people will want to work in the area that's getting the most funding.  For example, think about what happened when they put a lot of money into dealing with HIV/AIDS – it hurt the family planning program.  Also, with all these programs running at the same time, it gets really confusing.  You end up with a lot of repetition and paperwork.  It's not the most efficient way to do things.

Victorian novels are super detailed and super focused on the aristocracy, but not all of them are like that.  Two that stand out are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights.  These books have mystery and weirdness in them, which helps readers understand the characters better. It's like you get to see inside their heads and figure out what they're thinking and feeling.

I'm talking about the time I was walking with Sikes and Crackit, and we were yelling at each other.  It felt like the words we said were still echoing in my head, and when I tried to focus, I found myself talking to them.  Then there was this loud noise, like gunshots, and people were shouting and lights were flashing all around me.  I felt like I was being pulled away, but I couldn't control it.  There was this nagging feeling of pain that wouldn't go away – it was like someone was constantly poking at me.

In these two books, the authors use dreamlike scenes to show what's going on inside the characters' heads. In Oliver Twist, these visions often reveal stuff about Oliver's inner world, like what's bothering him and what he really thinks about what's happening. When Oliver gets shot, it's like he relives the whole thing in his head, over and over again.  He's trying to find help, but he's all numb and can't seem to do anything.  It's like his senses are all messed up, and he's stuck in this nightmare.  The whole thing is pretty overwhelming, and it makes you wonder who's really in control of Oliver's life – is it him, or is someone else calling the shots?  It's like he's given up, and that's not a good sign.

The next day was a blur – it felt like it came and went in an instant.  There was this endless, creepy silence, and then suddenly it was night again.  Night seemed to drag on and on, but at the same time, it felt like it was over before it even started.

A couple years ago, I had a pretty cool experience working in an after-school program where I helped Elementary age students with their schoolwork. I tried my best to assist them with whatever subject they were struggling with, but my strengths were in English and reading. One kid in particular caught my attention – a little dude named Adrian, who was maybe in third or fourth grade. He was having some major trouble reading, but it wasn't because he didn't understand the words, it was because he didn't know the English alphabet all that well. At first, I thought something was really off, like he had some sort of learning disability or something, but it turned out he was just missing the basics. I remember his mom walking in during one of our sessions, and she didn't speak a word of English – only Spanish. We managed to communicate somehow, but it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read just fine, but he just needed help with the alphabet. I'm not sure if that epiphany helped him much in the long run, but I hope he's doing better now. 

I tell this story because it highlights the problem of language barriers in schools, especially out here in California. It's not always as obvious as we think, and even for kids who speak perfect English, reading can still be super tough. Everyone agrees this is a problem, so the question is, what do we do? For Adrian, the solution was pretty simple: some extra help with English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciations. But for the kids who barely speak English, it's way more complicated. There's no one-size-fits-all answer. We've got dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes, and more – none of these things alone will fix the problem. The key is to combine them all.

The dual language system is actually a great idea, not just for kids who speak Spanish at home, but for all kids. Studies have shown that kids in two-way bilingual programs do way better academically. A lot of people are scared of this idea, thinking it's a waste of resources and that most kids won't benefit. But that's just not true. If we made these programs the norm, not the exception, all kids would benefit from them. So, how do we make this happen? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? That's unrealistic. What we can do is have special assistants, tutors, or whatever you call them, who are bilingual. That way, every kid can get the help they need to succeed.

We've all been told from a young age that there's something greater than us out there - something we can't quite wrap our heads around. We're sent to church, temple, or search within ourselves for answers. Many of us stick with what our parents taught us, while others reject it completely, convinced that there's nothing beyond our own little world. We might experiment with different values, switching from one to another, trying to figure out who we are through our own unique spiritual perspectives. We're all on a quest to find a guiding light in the darkness and push through the shadows into the light.

My dad and I sat on the porch, listening to the rain pelt the metal roof, when he told me his favourite bird was the cardinal. We both smoked our cigarettes in silence, surrounded by the sound of the rain pouring down through the gutters, drowning the plants along the edge of the porch. He gazed out into the rain, his eyes lost in thought, his body frail and thin from months of sickness. His hair had thinned out too, and his clothes hung loosely on him. I felt a mix of emotions: fear, sadness, and a desperate urge to talk to him about how much I'd miss him, but I knew that would only make it more real. Instead, I hugged him, sat back down, and joined him in staring out at the rain-soaked sky.

My dad passed away in December, just five days after my 22nd birthday. The chemo and radiation had prolonged his suffering, but it was a cruel joke - what was the point of living longer when it was just more pain? I'd stopped believing in God a long time ago, and I didn't bother with prayers that night. If he existed, he'd stopped listening to me a long time ago.

I didn't want to watch my dad slip away. So I didn't. I couldn't bear to see the person who created me die. I wanted to remember him by how he lived, not how he left this world. I knew my dad better than anyone, and I knew he wouldn't want his only child to be there for his death. For three days, I curled up in a ball and waited for the news. But when it finally came, there was no phone call.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is basically an oxymoron, where 'old' and 'new' blend together, as Ian Watt described it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. This genre has been both slammed and praised, accused of lacking depth, and admired for its 'terrible sublime' aspect (Burke).  The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, combined the ideas of old romance and modern novels to create the proto-Gothic genre. It was a new way of expressing literary ideas. Walpole used a mix of old theatrical elements and the modern novel's naturalism to present his "Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre borrowed from medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and customs. When The Castle of Otranto came out, the term "gothic" was already associated with different people, styles, and time periods. It was seen as outdated or unsophisticated compared to 'modern' societal and literary advancements. The blend of the theatrical "Gothic" and the novel's new format (which allowed readers to see the characters' psychology up close) helped the Gothic genre last and become both old and new to readers who were far away from the original writing.

One of the key gothic ideas in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval concept of chivalry, a knight's training process, is both kept and changed in the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is significant to Gothic writers because it represented the classic knight – brave, honorable, and capable – and the supposed lack of that ideal in society. Through the use of chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized (foreshadowing the evolution of Gothic to Romantic) and used to try to improve the present. Walpole, who wrote The Castle of Otranto during a time of political turmoil, was disheartened about the future and thought that the supposed morality and 'goodness' in people present in the gothic era had been lost in contemporary society. This is clear in his character Frederic, who is described as a prince who has suffered, been affected by tragedy, and is supposed to have been killed by infidels. The description of him includes many chivalric images, like being gallant and courteous. This exaggeration brings the Gothic trope of excess into play (66).

So I'm gonna tell you about supply chain management. It's like a big process of getting stuff from the customer's order all the way to the raw materials stage, then to supply, production, and finally to the customers. The term supply chain management was basically invented by Keith Oliver in 1982. He's a consultant and he described the whole process of planning, implementing, and controlling the chain to get stuff to customers super fast and efficiently. I mean, he made it sound so cool.

So there are six key things that make up a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these six things to give customers the best service ever. It's like a big puzzle that they have to figure out.

The first step in the puzzle is production. It's like the foundation of the whole thing. Production tells you when, why, where, and how stuff gets made. Managers have to know what customers want, right? They can check out the market to figure out what customers are looking for. The market is like a big indicator of what customers are demanding. Once they know what customers want, they can decide what to make, how much to make, and where to make it. They have to think about the customer's demand and satisfaction, you know?

For example, if I worked at Wal-Mart or Target, they would have a super cool design book with steps for every little thing, from what employees wear to how to get shipments from trucks. Having all that planned out helps the company avoid confusion and run smoothly.

The second key thing in supply chain management is supply. It's like making strategic decisions about what your company can do and who you can partner with. You might have different divisions for different products, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers have to decide which division is best for each product. Sometimes, they might even outsource work to other companies to make things faster and cheaper.

That's basically it, folks. Supply chain management is all about getting stuff to customers efficiently and effectively.

I saw a weird sign on the street today that said "Hitler is alive in Burma." Ellen Page, the Juno star, was holding that sign with a Sharpie, and it made me think of the country next to India, Myanmar, which is ruled by a super harsh military control group. They took over back in 1962. There were these big protests in 2007, the Saffron Revolution, where thousands of monks marched in the streets. The monks wore these bright orange robes, and it was a big deal. At first, the government was cool with them protesting, but things escalated quickly, and the monks and the military were fighting like crazy. The military even broke into some of the monasteries and arrested journalists who were just trying to report on the whole thing. A Japanese journalist got killed just for being there. The government says 13 people died, but another soldier who defected said way more people died, like thousands. It's not like this is a new thing, though. Governments have been trying to suppress people for as long as we've had societies. Even the ancient Romans thought their emperors were gods. The Japanese emperor is considered a god too, and some people think he brought us cell phones and cool ways to kill yourself. Even our current president talks to some dude named Ted Haggard who leads a group called the Stupid People Worldwide.

I was thinking about all the times when people tried to stand up to their governments and got crushed. Like that one time in China in 1989 when students and intellectuals protested and the government killed a bunch of them. We still don't know exactly how many died, but it was way more than what the government said. There was that other time in Rwanda in the 90s when the government helped kill all these people just because they were from a different group. And then there's the whole Hitler thing – he rounded up all these people just because of what they believed. It's just crazy.

Duke Ellington's impact on jazz is basically due to the fact that he was around for a long time and was super creative. This means he got to shape his orchestra in all sorts of ways. When you listen to a lot of his music, you might not notice him playing piano, but as a composer, he was totally awesome at making complex pieces that featured each musician's special talents. Ellington created the perfect setting for a soloist to improvise, and at the same time, he wrote music that was really tight and had certain sections with specific styles that fit the band members. He basically helped the whole orchestra sound like one coherent unit, creating unique sounds for each song. By understanding how each musician sounded separately and how they fit together, Ellington could write some of the most innovative music in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington's style and innovation, and mentions Creole Love Call as an example of him using voice as a jazz instrument throughout his career. This is like, an early example of Ellington's ability to mix voice with other sounds without words getting in the way. Creole Love Call also shows how Ellington could make the style of his soloists shine. This slow twelve bar blues piece has six choruses, which are kinda like the different parts of the song. Here's what each one's like:

Chorus 1: It's like a call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice starts smooth and then gets all rough at the end.
Chorus 2: There's a muted trumpet solo that takes the main melody and adds some extra blue notes.
Chorus 3: It's a really high clarinet solo with a piano phrase that's kinda syncopated.
Chorus 4: The whole band repeats the first chorus, but this time it's like a call and response between the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: This is the climactic part of the song, where the reeds start doing the call and response in a high register and the brass and rhythm sections are doing their own thing.
Chorus 6: It's back to the first chorus, but now the voice is doing this "growl" thing and soloing like an instrument.
Tag: There's a little tag at the end with a vocal run and some crazy notes from a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add a new dimension to his music is just one example of how he did things his own way and influenced a lot of other musicians. In Hot and Bothered, he uses his skills at making music sound really tight and his ear for tone color to create a really cool sound. In It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing), Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton to make the melody on muted trombone sound really cool.

It was this gnawing feeling that she'd had for years. It started when she hit 14 and entered the whirlwind of being a teenager. Even three years later, at 17, it was still there, driving her to think that she needed something more. But it wasn't a thing - it was a person. Yet, none of the guys she met seemed to be the one. Some had tried to swoop in, making awkward attempts to win her over, but nothing clicked. She'd often ask herself what was going on, wondering what it was that made a teenage girl feel this way. Years of pondering had brought up a bunch of theories, but none stuck.

Her home life was usually pretty chill. Her parents were good people, always calm and laid-back. They rarely fought, and when they did, it was usually about her desire for independence and her free-spirited nature. She was their calm daughter, but in a weird way, their opposing energies made her stand out - she was fun, outgoing, and nice.

Today, though, was a different story. As she wandered from room to room, searching for inspiration, she heard her mom's voice, laced with panic, coming from the kitchen. She ran in to find her mom on the ground, wincing in pain, saying "Ow" over and over. Her daughter rushed to her side, putting a hand on her to help, and asked, "Mom, what's wrong?! Mom, what's wrong?!" Her mom managed to stammer out, "Ouch...sweetie, I need you to take me to the hospital." Her daughter sprang into action, helping her mom to the car and driving her to the hospital.

The hospital was a place of disinfectant and fear, but she was too worried about her mom to feel it. She rushed her to the doctors, who quickly took her mom to get checked out. Her daughter was left pacing, worried sick. It turned out her mom had fallen off a step stool while trying to grab a vase from a high cabinet.

This study aimed to show that sticking to the Mediterranean Diet, known as the "aMed diet", helps cut down on the risk of heart disease and stroke. The aMed diet is a special version of the traditional Mediterranean diet and is all about eating more plant foods, like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, and less animal products and fats. 

Previous studies had already found that people who follow the Mediterranean diet are less likely to die from heart problems, and another study proved that it's even better than a low-fat diet for losing weight and lowering bad cholesterol levels in obese people. However, these studies didn't look at the impact of the diet on stroke specifically.

The study looked at 74,886 female nurses, aged 38 to 63, who were already participating in a big research project called the Nurses' Health Study. Over 20 years, from 1984 to 2004, the researchers calculated how well each nurse followed the aMed diet by asking them about their eating habits in surveys every six years. Almost all of the nurses kept participating for the whole 20 years. The researchers also checked the nurses' medical records to see if they had heart problems or strokes and made sure that the information was accurate. 

To get a better picture of the nurses' eating habits over time, the researchers averaged out their aMed diet scores from their surveys over the years. They also adjusted for things that could affect the results, such as the nurses' age, weight, smoking habits, and exercise routine.

Using special math, the researchers found that women who followed the Mediterranean diet closely had a lower risk of getting heart disease and stroke. After 20 years, they found 2391 cases of heart disease, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 heart disease deaths. The women who followed the diet the best were less likely to get heart disease and stroke compared to those who followed it the least.

It's crazy to think that like, 15 years ago, the United States went through a major financial crisis. People lost their jobs, houses were becoming worthless, and huge corporations were on the verge of collapse. So, the question remains: how did this all go down, and how can we avoid it happening again? The whole thing started with some pretty silly and not-so-smart political decisions that basically forced banks to give out bad loans to people who couldn't afford them. At the same time, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were being pressured into buying up these bad mortgages and turning them into even more complicated financial messes. When people started defaulting on their loans, the banks were left in a tough spot and just shifted the blame to the people who bought those bad mortgages from them.

It all started to unravel back in the late 90s, when President Clinton was trying to get re-elected. He relaxed some rules, hoping to make himself look good, and that's when things started to go downhill. In 1999, Steven Holmes from the New York Times wrote, "Fannie Mae was under a lot of pressure from the government to give out more loans to people who can barely afford them, and from stockholders to keep making money." He basically predicted that this would all end badly: "This government-subsidized company might get into trouble when the economy slows down, and we might need to bail them out like we did with the savings and loan industry back in the 80s." 

A bunch of other factors contributed to the whole mess, like the crazy new types of mortgages people were getting, such as adjustable-rate mortgages and CDOs. This just made things way more complicated and connected to the housing market. It was like, people and banks got in way over their heads, and when the housing bubble burst, they were all like, "What do we do now?" The top five investment banks in the US had like, $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, which was a third of the country's GDP. In the end, some of these banks got sold super cheap, others got shut down, and Fannie and Freddie were basically taken over by the government because they were so deep in debt.

Exposition - that infamous section in your story where you spread your wings as a writer but end up putting most of your readers to sleep or making them hit the "Back" button in frustration. Dr. Merlin has been known to yell at her monitor when she gets stuck in the land of Too Much Information, and for good reason. Exposition is not your BFF (best friend forever).

You probably know the drill: "Show, don't tell." But Dr. Merlin still finds herself rambling on with unnecessary backstory, or worse, dragging readers through a boring forest of details. Exposition is that pesky voice in your head that says, "Get the history over with so we can get to the good stuff." Just don't confuse it with the other voice that's all like, "Tell us everything about the main character's mom's cat."

So, what is exposition, exactly? It's when you tell your readers what happened instead of showing them. Think about it like a film where one character is dumping a huge load of info on another character, like in "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, you're the one doing the dumping.

Let's look at an example. Imagine you're reading a story and it goes something like this: "The heroine met her husband at such and such a time, and they got married in a big way, but he ended up getting murdered in front of her. Yeah, that's it." You wouldn't expect a two-page explanation of the whole thing, with only two lines of dialogue from the couple. That's just boring. What you'd want is to see how much the husband loves his wife through the way he talks and acts, and how her life changes with him. If the story later says they had a deep connection, you'd want to see evidence of that in the story itself. You'd get to experience the husband's death with the heroine and become more connected to her character.

So, as a writer, you need to add some meat to the bare bones of the storyline. It's tempting to rush through certain parts, but don't - take the time to develop your characters and make them real. You might know that your character used to be in the Air Force, works at a gas station at night, and dreams of owning the place one day, but do you really need to tell us all that at once? Keep it simple and let your readers experience it through the story itself.

Today I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one I saw was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011), and guess what? It was a live show! The leading story was about a sick guy in Ashley, Ohio who stabbed his wife - they didn't say her name, just his, Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot, and let me tell you, he looked like a total creep. They only gave it two minutes, which I thought was fair since the story was still developing. The details they did give were pretty basic - he stabbed her a bunch of times and got arrested.

The second story was about a shooting involving an 18-year-old kid named Travis Buyers in the Sharon Woods area. He got shot and was in critical condition, but no arrests had been made, and there were no suspects yet. The SWAT Team was investigating, which seemed a little weird considering there wasn't much info on the case. I've noticed this before: minorities get glossed over when they're victims of a crime. For some reason, if it's a white person who gets hurt or kidnapped, the media goes crazy, but if it's a minority, it's like they're not even important. 

Next up was a story about a gunshot hole in the Med-Flight helicopter. They gave some details about where they think the incident happened and what kind of bullet was used (a .22 caliber from a rifle). They're offering a five-thousand dollar reward for anyone who can give 'em a lead on the shooter.

The next story was about the rain and thunderstorms that were supposed to hit on Saturday afternoon. They said the temps would be in the mid to low eighties for the weekend, but that was about it - I guess they wanted to leave us hanging so we'd keep watching.

They also covered a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said the thief was a black guy wearing a hoodie sweatshirt, about six-foot-tall and 150 pounds. They made a big deal about how dark-skinned he was, which seemed kinda weird.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, some dude who got convicted of smuggling a bunch of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. He got sentenced to 300 months in prison (which I guess means 25 years, but I'm not really sure why they said it that way). They also mentioned he's Hispanic, which I don't think was really necessary.

There's a deep, unbreakable connection between brothers that's hard to put into words. This bond is made up of a mix of feelings, including love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. Brothers have this unique understanding of each other that's hard to find with anyone else. They can see themselves through their brother's eyes, and it's only when things get really tough that the true nature of this bond shows up – whether it's good or bad. However, it comes at a cost, and part of understanding this bond means dealing with the consequences that come with it. When you look into your brother's eyes, you see your own reflection staring back, and it's a look at yourself, not as others see you, but as you really are.  In the long run, it's the choices you make and the consequences that follow that show your true character.

In the story "The Scarlet Ibis," this theme is really brought out through the two brothers' crazy, intense emotions. They're on this wild, impossible journey, and in the end, bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in a super dramatic moment. Only one of them makes it out alive. The author uses the protagonist's character and how he interacts with his brother, as well as the narrator's point of view, to show just how complicated these feelings can be. The whole story is centered around one main emotion: pride. From the very start, the protagonist feels really resentful towards his little brother, Doodle. He wanted a brother who could do all the cool stuff he was good at, like holding his breath or climbing trees. But Doodle was born with a weak heart, and it was clear he'd never be able to do those things. The protagonist's whole world was crushed when he realized his dreams were gone. In fact, he even thought about hurting his little brother at one point, which is pretty shocking. But when Doodle smiles, it makes the protagonist's heart melt. It shows that deep down, he really loved his brother and didn't want to hurt him. This whole thing is a wild ride, and it's amazing how easy it is to get caught up in your own emotions and forget what's most important.

The brain is like a super cool, super complicated info machine that's been around for a long time. Over time, people have used all sorts of cool metaphors to describe it. They first compared it to a wax tablet, then a piece of papyrus, then a book, and now to a computer. But keep in mind that these metaphors aren't perfect and can lead to some pretty wild conclusions.

So here's how it works: your senses like eyes, ears, and skin take in the physical stuff around you, like touch, heat, sound, or light. They turn that into a secret language that the brain can understand. This information gets processed over and over again in two ways: bottom-up and top-down. For example, when you look at a picture of a black box, your brain puts together simple stuff like color, shape, and where the edges are to figure out that it's a box. Then, it uses what it's already learned to help you recognize the box even faster. It's like when you look at a picture of a pizza and your brain is like, "Oh, it's a circle with cheese and sauce!"

Once the brain's processed the info to some extent, it decides how important it is and which other brain processes it should get to look at it. For instance, you might be walking through the park and your brain is processing every single blade of grass, but it only lets you notice the really important stuff, like the person talking to you. There are a lot of stages of processing, and the brain's like, "Hey, I think this is cool, let me take a closer look!" or "Nope, this isn't that important, move on!"

For the brain to process info, it needs to store it first. There are different kinds of memory, like sensory, working, and long-term. First, it gets encoded, which is like putting a code on it. There are different types of encoding for different kinds of sensory stuff. For example, if you read a word, it gets encoded based on how it looks, what it sounds like, or what it means. Once it's stored, it needs to be kept safe. Studies on animals suggest that working memory, which lasts for about 20 seconds, is like a temporary electrical signal that keeps going for a little while. Long-term memory is thought to be stored in the structure of special proteins.

There are a bunch of different models of how knowledge is organized in the brain, like the way people remember stuff, how computers work, or how our brains are wired. The semantic network model says that there are like nodes that represent ideas, and they're connected based on how related they are. For example, the idea of a chair might be linked to a table, which is linked to wood, and so on.

It's like Aldous Huxley was totally worried about how technology and capitalism were becoming super threatening in the novel Brave New World. He imagined a future where people would actually be more into being part of a community than being individuals. They'd be brainwashed from birth to go for immediate happiness over everything else. It's like these people were just pawns in some giant game, forced to stick to one way of thinking by the World Controller. If you look at the book through the lens of Marxist ideas, you can tell Huxley was really skeptical about the whole system. He used a lot of terms from Marxism, like how people become the same and stuff gets turned into objects, to show how he thought the capitalist system was messed up.

He also used satire to make fun of capitalism by saying that people are tricked into not knowing the real deal about the classes in society. It's like, the common people only care about their own stuff, and they don't really get how things work. This is because the people in charge are controlling what they think and want. The lower classes, like the Deltas and Gammas, just go along with it because they're conditioned to want to buy and spend and indulge. It's all manipulated by the World Controller, who's like the ultimate puppet master.

It's pretty obvious that the lower classes are being dominated by the upper classes. They're like, completely clueless about the system, just 'buying into' an idea that keeps them in their place. Even the upper classes, like the Alphas and Betas, just go along with it. They're not really doing anything to change things. The way the different classes interact with each other is a big clue about how capitalism is oppressing people.

In Brave New World, relationships between people are super shallow. The characters are basically just one-dimensional. It's like Huxley is saying that technology and capitalism are taking away people's free will and creativity. Love and strong emotions don't exist; people just talk about how good-looking someone is, or how great their experiences are. Each class is just happy with their place in society, which is a big sign of how capitalism is affecting people. They're just obeying the rules and doing what they're told, like the Marxist idea of the proletariat being tricked into thinking they're better than everyone else if they just consume and follow the rules.

I've been a student at University Park for about two and a half years now - or four and a half semesters if you count the semesters. It's a big campus, and getting around can be a real drag. Last year I was stuck in an East Halls dorm room, which is pretty far out there, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Going from my Stuart Hall home to classes in places like the Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially if it's raining or something. I talked to an alum who's not much older than me, and they told me that not long ago, East Halls was basically a separate part of campus, surrounded by empty space. Now that's all filled up with sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and the health services building, and apartments. As the campus keeps growing, it's getting harder to get from one place to another. So, what's the solution to this problem? On a college campus, I think the best answer is the humble bike. But it's not just about having a bike - people actually have to ride them, and the campus needs to be bike-friendly.

I was talking to a friend who got back into biking after a few years off, and he was saying how he wondered why he ever stopped. "Bikes are awesome," he said. "For a while, it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Plus, biking is great for your body, and it's super efficient. I can eat a bowl of oatmeal and ride my bike 30 miles or more. I live off campus now, just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. Getting a bike was one of the smartest things I did this year. I have class in Thomas building every day, which is a 25-minute walk from my place. But with a bike, I can get there in 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The problem is, Pollock Road is the shortest route to Thomas, but it's not always easy to ride on. I also like biking because I'm too busy to walk, and walking would take up way too much of my time. If I didn't have my bike, I'd have to walk to Thomas every day, which would take an extra 30-40 minutes. That's over two and a half hours every week, and I just don't have that kind of time to waste.
